WEBVTT

00:00.403 --> 00:02.887
Sync and corrections by n17t01
www.addic7ed.com

00:02.982 --> 00:04.261
[ Crows caw ]

00:05.272 --> 00:07.502
[ Breathing deeply ]

00:07.802 --> 00:09.408
I think she misses her.

00:09.754 --> 00:11.260
We all do, Sue.

00:12.146 --> 00:13.332
I can't believe
I'm the last one

00:13.423 --> 00:15.033
who saw Aunt Edie alive.

00:15.104 --> 00:16.606
I was just here reading her
the crime report

00:16.669 --> 00:19.086
from the "Orson Herald,"
and she seemed fine.

00:19.182 --> 00:20.985
She lit a cigarette
with another cigarette

00:21.093 --> 00:23.766
and then said,
"Thanks for stopping by, Axl."

00:23.906 --> 00:25.256
- Aw.
- Aw.

00:25.377 --> 00:26.904
I remember when I was little

00:27.027 --> 00:28.756
and she'd have
her holiday parties,

00:28.846 --> 00:30.934
and I would go around
to all the adults

00:31.023 --> 00:33.249
with my little
toy drink cartons,

00:33.324 --> 00:35.827
and I would say, "Do you want
chocolate milk or orange juice?",

00:35.932 --> 00:37.328
and they'd all say,
"Oh, how nice",

00:37.434 --> 00:38.545
and I'd get to Aunt Edie

00:38.646 --> 00:41.041
and she'd say, "Shut up
and make me a real drink."

00:41.125 --> 00:42.287
Aw.

00:42.713 --> 00:44.202
Okay, enough reminiscing.

00:44.287 --> 00:45.784
Today's not
about getting emotional.

00:45.870 --> 00:48.502
It's about finding paperwork
and cleaning up.

00:48.598 --> 00:52.508
Okay, so we're looking for
a birth certificate, a will,

00:52.562 --> 00:54.637
- a napkin, any--
- I think I found it.

00:55.667 --> 00:58.299
[ Sighs ] No,
it's another portable bar.

01:00.422 --> 01:01.570
What's this?

01:03.904 --> 01:06.735
Oh, it's a picture
of the Leilani Motor Lodge

01:06.834 --> 01:07.656
in South Dakota.

01:07.736 --> 01:09.028
It's where Aunt Edie
honeymooned.

01:09.109 --> 01:10.476
What, was North Dakota closed?

01:10.626 --> 01:12.617
No, after she married
her first husband Carl,

01:12.701 --> 01:15.236
they lived in South Dakota,
and Aunt Edie always said

01:15.303 --> 01:17.083
she wanted to get
back to the Leilani,

01:17.165 --> 01:18.702
but now she never will.

01:18.867 --> 01:20.052
Aw.

01:20.562 --> 01:21.521
<i>[ Big band playing</i>
<i>slow-tempo jazz ]</i>

01:21.615 --> 01:23.807
This was
Aunt Edie's favorite song.

01:23.967 --> 01:25.494
- Aw.
- Aw.

01:25.510 --> 01:27.343
All right, everyone,
stop remembering things.

01:27.457 --> 01:29.216
We're looking
for important papers.

01:29.459 --> 01:31.815
- Like this?
- Ooh!

01:31.954 --> 01:35.597
Okay, well, we got
a birth certificate.

01:35.847 --> 01:37.900
Social Security card.

01:38.131 --> 01:40.842
Coupon from Elaine Powers.

01:41.250 --> 01:43.283
Oh, this is some kind
of official statement

01:43.373 --> 01:45.843
saying she made a payment
on a burial plot.

01:46.267 --> 01:49.067
Aw, she wants to be buried
next to Carl.

01:49.178 --> 01:50.312
Where's Carl?

01:51.170 --> 01:52.678
South Dakota.

01:52.812 --> 01:53.907
[ Record needle scratches ]

01:54.079 --> 01:55.085
Sorry.

01:55.187 --> 01:56.442
Can you hand me that briefcase?

01:56.549 --> 01:57.932
Oh, it's a portable bar.

01:58.092 --> 01:59.278
I know.

02:00.515 --> 02:03.175
<i>[ Train horn blows,</i>
<i>wheels chugging ]</i>

02:05.477 --> 02:07.479
I still don't know why
we didn't just drive.

02:07.725 --> 02:09.675
Because you do for family.

02:09.773 --> 02:11.116
This is our final show
of respect.

02:11.195 --> 02:13.266
We're not just gonna
ship her off like luggage.

02:13.396 --> 02:14.632
So where is she now?

02:14.720 --> 02:16.517
She's resting comfortably
in cargo.

02:16.757 --> 02:19.588
Do we have any details about
the cause of Aunt Edie's death?

02:19.676 --> 02:21.796
Just one. She was 96.

02:21.882 --> 02:25.649
Interesting. Has anyone
questioned Helen Riley?

02:25.726 --> 02:26.893
She was the perennial runner-up
to Aunt Edie

02:26.971 --> 02:28.447
in the church pie contest.

02:28.538 --> 02:29.867
No one hated Aunt Edie, Brick.

02:29.917 --> 02:30.683
She was a great lady,

02:30.772 --> 02:32.718
and we were lucky to have her
for as long as we did.

02:33.351 --> 02:35.131
Sue:
Well, I loved Aunt Edie.

02:35.229 --> 02:37.640
But this could <i> not</i>
have happened at a worse time.

02:37.783 --> 02:39.073
I carved out the whole weekend

02:39.132 --> 02:40.677
to finish my common app
for college.

02:40.778 --> 02:42.453
Axl: Would you stop thinking
about yourself, Sue?

02:42.571 --> 02:43.476
Aunt Edie's gone forever,

02:43.550 --> 02:46.294
and family's the most important
thing right now.

02:47.967 --> 02:50.342
Wow. He seems really broken up.

02:50.654 --> 02:52.803
Almost <i> too</i> broken up.

02:54.762 --> 02:58.316
<i>[ Train horn blows,</i>
<i>wheels chugging ]</i>

02:59.383 --> 03:00.862
[ Indistinct conversations ]

03:01.589 --> 03:02.708
Are you okay?

03:02.889 --> 03:06.048
No, Brick, I'm not.
I killed Aunt Edie.

03:06.140 --> 03:09.308
I knew it! No one just
drops dead at 96.

03:09.463 --> 03:12.962
No... [ Sighs ] I didn't really kill her.

03:13.944 --> 03:16.089
Okay. Ugh. Look.
Here's the thing.

03:16.236 --> 03:17.413
[ Sniffles ]
Ever since high school,

03:17.519 --> 03:19.813
whenever I had a test
I wasn't ready for,

03:19.918 --> 03:21.113
or a paper due I didn't finish,

03:21.220 --> 03:24.037
I kinda used Aunt Edie
to get out of it.

03:24.932 --> 03:27.358
Anyway, we just found out
last night,

03:27.487 --> 03:29.370
so I think I'm gonna need
a little more time

03:29.496 --> 03:31.139
on my philosophy paper.

03:31.250 --> 03:33.887
Of course.
And just remember, Axl,

03:34.028 --> 03:37.185
it was your aunt's shell
she left on Earth.

03:37.297 --> 03:40.712
It was her shell.
So, like, three extra weeks?

03:42.443 --> 03:44.089
Can't you see how guilty
I feel about this?!

03:44.246 --> 03:45.476
If my hair wasn't such
a perfect length,

03:45.541 --> 03:47.176
I could barely look at myself
in the mirror.

03:47.267 --> 03:48.237
I used my aunt's life

03:48.338 --> 03:49.904
as a cheap excuse
to get out of schoolwork,

03:49.993 --> 03:52.896
and by saying it so many times,
I'm the reason she died.

03:52.992 --> 03:55.154
I killed her, Brick.
I killed my aunt!

03:58.714 --> 04:01.740
Ugh. I am so hungry.
I can't concentrate.

04:01.866 --> 04:03.190
Are we ever gonna eat?

04:03.303 --> 04:05.546
I'm not paying 8 bucks
for a Coke and an Oh Henry!

04:06.373 --> 04:07.788
Sue, how's your essay coming?

04:07.875 --> 04:09.774
Okay. I don't wanna get ahead
of myself,

04:09.870 --> 04:12.469
but I think so far,
really great.

04:12.556 --> 04:13.675
You wanna hear some of it?

04:13.797 --> 04:14.737
- Of course.
- That's okay.

04:14.811 --> 04:15.973
Okay. [ Clears throat ]

04:16.058 --> 04:16.918
"My dad told me

04:17.000 --> 04:20.012
to wait to see what happens
in life and then label it.

04:20.970 --> 04:24.345
But I say, no, I named this
'The Year Of Sue,'

04:24.450 --> 04:26.896
and since then,
great things have happened."

04:27.027 --> 04:28.777
I think colleges are really
gonna respond to this,

04:28.866 --> 04:29.970
because more than anything,

04:30.055 --> 04:32.228
they want
the shooting for the stars type.

04:32.297 --> 04:33.549
[ Gasps ] New title--

04:33.677 --> 04:35.531
"Shooting For The Stars."

04:35.626 --> 04:37.112
So did we check the coffin
to make sure

04:37.189 --> 04:39.297
- Aunt Edie's in there?
- Brick, listen to me.

04:39.423 --> 04:42.222
She just got old and died,
but it's okay.

04:42.311 --> 04:44.785
She had a great ride. She met
a lot of wonderful people.

04:44.877 --> 04:46.690
She saw a lot
of wonderful places.

04:46.804 --> 04:49.912
She really did everything
she wanted to in life.

04:50.086 --> 04:52.860
Actually, she did it
with about 20 years to spare.

04:53.782 --> 04:55.742
You're right.

04:56.395 --> 04:57.823
Well, what have I done
in my life?

04:57.910 --> 04:58.896
I haven't done anything.

04:58.973 --> 04:59.975
I've just laid around
reading books

05:00.070 --> 05:02.357
about other people
doing things.

05:03.474 --> 05:04.888
If Aunt Edie's taught me
anything,

05:05.017 --> 05:08.238
it's that life is waiting.
Mom, take my book.

05:08.336 --> 05:09.747
From now on,
Brick Heck's gonna step

05:09.827 --> 05:12.251
outside his comfort zone
and start living.

05:12.319 --> 05:13.996
And what better place
than on a train?

05:18.823 --> 05:20.813
Frankie: <i>So Mike and I crunched</i>
<i>the numbers and figured</i>

05:20.895 --> 05:23.503
<i>we could spring for a plate</i>
<i>of chicken fingers.</i>

05:23.590 --> 05:25.636
Excuse me. I don't think you
gave us enough chicken fingers.

05:25.783 --> 05:27.257
You asked for one order.

05:27.359 --> 05:29.466
Yeah, but shouldn't there
be at least five?

05:29.646 --> 05:31.233
I mean, there's five fingers.
You know, if you count

05:31.289 --> 05:32.977
the thumb as a finger,
which most people do.

05:33.035 --> 05:34.466
And if you're talking
<i>actual</i> chicken fingers,

05:34.529 --> 05:36.480
I think they have
at least seven.

05:41.119 --> 05:43.505
[ Under breath ] Lot of attitude
for a train bartender.

05:46.561 --> 05:47.342
Oh.

05:47.464 --> 05:48.952
Oh, my God.
Are you all right?

05:49.024 --> 05:50.546
- Yeah, I'm fine.
- Are you sure?

05:50.704 --> 05:52.010
You fell pretty hard there.

05:52.087 --> 05:53.760
I know. I fall.

05:53.835 --> 05:55.745
I-I fall all the time.
It's stupid. I know.

05:55.820 --> 05:57.049
Here. Why don't you sit down
for a second?

05:57.113 --> 05:58.402
Oh, thanks. That's a good idea.

05:58.506 --> 06:00.495
Oh, you're being so helpful.
I really appreciate it.

06:00.560 --> 06:01.556
Oh, no, it's nothing.

06:04.596 --> 06:06.221
[ Whispers ] Take care.

06:08.904 --> 06:10.298
[ Mouths words ]

06:16.978 --> 06:18.091
What are you doing?

06:18.268 --> 06:21.080
I'll tell you what I'm doing.
I'm living life.

06:21.270 --> 06:23.757
- [ Groans ]
- Look at all the dead trees and brown grass.

06:23.851 --> 06:26.251
I can't believe I've been
missing all of this. Mm.

06:26.410 --> 06:29.007
Oh, no. No, no, no,
no, no, no, no, no.

06:29.123 --> 06:30.849
- This can't be happening.
- What?

06:30.971 --> 06:32.739
My phone! It was working
just a minute ago,

06:32.827 --> 06:34.286
and now it's completely
out of juice.

06:34.398 --> 06:35.993
[ Groans ] Trapped on
a 20-hour train ride

06:36.113 --> 06:39.164
to South Dakota with no phone
and just my family to talk to.

06:39.244 --> 06:44.035
[ Gasps ] It's Aunt Edie.
She's getting her revenge.

06:44.088 --> 06:45.034
I've killed her so many times.

06:45.159 --> 06:46.522
Now she's killed my phone.

06:46.621 --> 06:49.212
You don't need a screen
to look at, Axl.

06:49.338 --> 06:51.772
You're looking
at the best screen ever--

06:51.929 --> 06:53.553
- Iowa in the winter.
- [ Groans ]

06:53.670 --> 06:56.513
Soak it in, my friend.
Soak it in.

06:58.548 --> 06:59.889
It's just embarrassing, Mike.

07:00.014 --> 07:01.505
It's embarrassing that I fell,

07:01.680 --> 07:03.545
and my husband wasn't
the one to pick me up.

07:03.636 --> 07:05.555
Look, I was on my way
to help you.

07:05.672 --> 07:06.939
The guy just beat me to it.

07:07.040 --> 07:09.418
[ Scoffs ] Okay.

07:09.710 --> 07:11.072
What does that mean?

07:11.199 --> 07:12.744
It means, apparently,
it's more important

07:12.838 --> 07:15.485
for you to get ketchup than
to come and help your wife.

07:15.616 --> 07:17.094
Yeah, I saw.

07:17.255 --> 07:19.195
I was in the middle of pumping.

07:19.507 --> 07:21.049
There's a rhythm
to those dispensers.

07:21.145 --> 07:23.366
It goes pump, pump, pump.
[ Imitates squirt ]

07:23.547 --> 07:25.224
And then a reset.
You gotta pump all the way

07:25.302 --> 07:27.142
through to the reset,
or you wreck your rhythm.

07:27.252 --> 07:27.937
Whatever, Mike.

07:28.040 --> 07:29.390
The important thing
is you got your ketchup.

07:29.546 --> 07:31.722
I'm just happy there was
one gentleman on the train.

07:31.836 --> 07:34.900
Look, you fell, and I didn't
help you. I'm sorry.

07:35.001 --> 07:36.544
What else can I do?

07:37.406 --> 07:39.768
I'm sorry to bother you.
I saw you fall earlier,

07:39.871 --> 07:41.525
and it looked like you might
have twisted your ankle,

07:41.623 --> 07:43.429
so I brought you an ice pack.

07:43.598 --> 07:45.886
Thank you so much.

07:46.172 --> 07:47.773
Yeah. Thanks!

07:48.274 --> 07:49.233
[ Plastic rustles ]

07:50.473 --> 07:54.357
<i>[ Train horn blows,</i>
<i>wheels chugging ]</i>

07:58.223 --> 07:59.664
Look, I really am sorry.

07:59.812 --> 08:01.719
[ Scoffs ] You know what?
It's fine.

08:01.799 --> 08:02.758
You're just not a nurturer.

08:02.873 --> 08:04.579
But that's okay.
I've made my peace with it.

08:04.662 --> 08:06.833
What are you talking about?
I... nurture.

08:06.927 --> 08:08.625
[ Sighs ] You realize
that when I found out

08:08.699 --> 08:11.090
Aunt Edie had died,
you didn't even hug me?

08:11.199 --> 08:12.566
- Sure, I did.
- No, you didn't.

08:12.663 --> 08:15.687
You patted me. It was a pat.
Pat, pat, pat.

08:15.843 --> 08:18.501
- You're remembering it wrong.
- No, I'm not.

08:18.615 --> 08:20.011
They told me Aunt Edie
had died.

08:20.121 --> 08:21.757
I hung up the phone.
You said...

08:21.840 --> 08:23.236
[ Imitates Mike ] "Well,
we knew that call was coming."

08:23.303 --> 08:24.309
[ Normal voice ]
Then you patted me

08:24.433 --> 08:26.471
like a golden retriever
and you went and watched TV.

08:26.638 --> 08:27.871
You've never been a hugger,
Mike.

08:27.969 --> 08:29.553
When the kids were younger,
they hugged me all the time,

08:29.640 --> 08:32.003
so I didn't really notice,
but now it's very clear.

08:32.094 --> 08:33.725
I'm trapped
in a hugless marriage.

08:35.052 --> 08:37.041
You wanna try
a wordless marriage?

08:37.164 --> 08:38.226
[ Scoffs ]

08:38.395 --> 08:41.294
Fine. Prove me wrong.
Nurture me.

08:41.409 --> 08:42.232
Ugh.

08:42.296 --> 08:43.902
Look me in the eyes
for more than two seconds

08:44.006 --> 08:45.256
and tell me that you love me.

08:45.346 --> 08:46.566
Right now in front of people?

08:47.410 --> 08:49.399
Hug me, then.
No, not even a hug.

08:49.515 --> 08:52.823
Just-- just put your arm
around me and comfort me.

08:59.916 --> 09:01.152
[ Scoffs ]
Is there a problem?

09:01.235 --> 09:02.891
No. It's that
the angle's weird.

09:03.554 --> 09:05.548
You weren't worried about
weird angles the other night.

09:05.646 --> 09:06.715
Here I am, Mike.

09:06.836 --> 09:09.432
Just nurture me as you see fit.

09:14.732 --> 09:16.087
That's a pat.

09:24.745 --> 09:25.820
Hey.

09:25.936 --> 09:26.787
Hey.

09:26.926 --> 09:28.022
Yeah.

09:33.399 --> 09:35.686
I'm going to visit my uncle.
He's a rancher.

09:36.280 --> 09:39.807
Rancher. Cool.

09:40.073 --> 09:41.411
He's got
these awesome dirt bikes

09:41.507 --> 09:42.941
that I pop wheelies on.

09:43.036 --> 09:45.365
Dirt bikes. Cool.

09:51.929 --> 09:53.119
[ Mouth full ] Beef jerky?

09:53.216 --> 09:55.049
Beef jerky. Cool.

09:57.000 --> 10:03.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

10:09.296 --> 10:11.540
Stop patting me. It's over.

10:11.789 --> 10:12.943
I made a friend.

10:13.741 --> 10:14.930
What? Where?

10:15.147 --> 10:17.922
Here. He's this really cool guy
named Travis, and he likes me.

10:18.023 --> 10:20.660
[ Gasps ] Mike, wake up.
Somebody likes Brick.

10:20.760 --> 10:21.906
What? Who?

10:22.008 --> 10:24.399
It turns out I'm cool
on trains.

10:24.514 --> 10:25.627
That's great, Brick.

10:25.735 --> 10:27.432
So what do you and Travis
talk about?

10:27.574 --> 10:28.216
Nothing.

10:28.323 --> 10:29.866
I figured out
all I have to do is repeat

10:29.963 --> 10:32.689
what the other person says
and then add the word "cool."

10:32.820 --> 10:34.143
All these years I've been
repeating myself

10:34.258 --> 10:35.818
when I should've been
repeating other people.

10:35.932 --> 10:38.254
[ Whispers ]
Repeating other people.

10:38.626 --> 10:39.764
Travis reminded me to have
breakfast

10:39.842 --> 10:42.105
with him when the dining car
opens. Can I go?

10:42.255 --> 10:45.007
If he's buying, order extra
and bring some back.

10:45.137 --> 10:49.536
Bring some back. Cool.
Magic, am I right?

10:55.538 --> 10:56.326
[ Groans softly ]

10:57.132 --> 11:00.879
<i>[ Train horn blows,</i>
<i>wheels chugging ]</i>

11:01.382 --> 11:02.579
Axl!

11:03.129 --> 11:05.320
What? Ow! Oh.
Come on, Aunt Edie.

11:05.501 --> 11:06.866
Hmm! I'm finally done.

11:07.036 --> 11:09.061
Here. Listen to the last line
of my essay.

11:09.178 --> 11:10.674
It's <i> really, really</i> good.

11:11.676 --> 11:13.551
"And in conclusion, that is why

11:13.656 --> 11:16.928
I'll spend the rest of my life
shooting at the cars and..."

11:17.586 --> 11:21.755
"Shooting at the cars"?
Oh, pfft. Oh, God. I <i> am</i> tired.

11:21.884 --> 11:24.079
- It's a good thing I'm proofreading this.
- [ Typing ]

11:24.182 --> 11:24.995
[ Brakes squeal, clank ]

11:25.070 --> 11:26.290
[ Computer chimes ]

11:26.502 --> 11:27.586
[ Beep ]

11:27.852 --> 11:28.906
Wait a minute.
What just happened?

11:28.988 --> 11:30.250
Where did it go?

11:30.335 --> 11:32.404
"Congratulations.
Your application has been sent."

11:32.464 --> 11:36.043
[ Gasps ] No, no, no, no,
I accidentally hit "Send"!

11:36.114 --> 11:37.516
Axl: - Classic. [ Laughs ]
- [ Sue gasps ]

11:37.601 --> 11:40.112
No, no, no, no, no!
My life is over!

11:40.233 --> 11:41.730
- Hey, what's wrong?
- What'd you do, Axl?

11:41.822 --> 11:43.608
[ Gasps ] I was working
on my essay,

11:43.711 --> 11:44.636
and it was all done,

11:44.715 --> 11:46.051
and I wanted to write
"Shooting for the stars,"

11:46.155 --> 11:47.702
but instead I wrote
"Shooting at the cars,"

11:47.807 --> 11:49.831
so I tried to hit "Delete,"
and then the train lurched

11:49.964 --> 11:50.876
and I hit "Send" instead,

11:50.980 --> 11:52.822
and now I'm never
gonna go to college!

11:52.898 --> 11:53.957
You got this.

11:55.505 --> 11:56.509
Honey, can't you just tell
the school

11:56.622 --> 11:58.060
you accidentally sent it?

11:58.147 --> 11:59.973
It's not just one school.
It's the common app.

12:00.076 --> 12:02.441
This went to every school
I applied to.

12:02.567 --> 12:06.060
Well, just relax. I'm sure
there's something we can do.

12:06.143 --> 12:08.356
What can we do?
Can we turn off the internet?

12:08.451 --> 12:09.687
Is there a button
for when the train lurches

12:09.772 --> 12:10.979
and you accidentally
hit "Send"?

12:11.085 --> 12:12.443
Is there a computer expert
on this train

12:12.516 --> 12:14.924
who specializes
in college applications?!

12:16.671 --> 12:18.358
I'm more thirsty than hungry.

12:18.557 --> 12:20.466
- More thirsty. Cool.
- [ Microwave beeps ]

12:21.655 --> 12:23.138
- Here's what we're gonna do.
- [ Microwave door opens ]

12:23.239 --> 12:24.463
You're gonna distract
the bartender,

12:24.580 --> 12:26.428
then I'm gonna steal some beer.

12:26.537 --> 12:28.658
- Got it?
- Steal a beer.

12:29.186 --> 12:29.909
[ Microwave door closes ]

12:29.995 --> 12:32.202
Cool.
[ Chuckles nervously ]

12:33.009 --> 12:35.110
- [ Bell clanging in distance ]
- Axl, Axl. [ Sighs ]

12:35.234 --> 12:37.523
- Ow. Ow. - You know more
about computer stuff than I do.

12:37.618 --> 12:38.927
Can you please just see
if there's any way

12:39.002 --> 12:40.175
you can get my essay back?

12:40.265 --> 12:41.641
Well...
[ Scoffs and trills lips ]

12:41.713 --> 12:42.844
I don't know, Sue.
I think it's done.

12:42.915 --> 12:44.148
I mean, look,
it sent you a receipt

12:44.225 --> 12:45.394
of the schools you applied to.

12:45.486 --> 12:48.705
- [ Whimpers ]
- Uh... Indiana, Purdue, Ball State.

12:48.787 --> 12:49.899
East Indiana St--
[ Gasps ]

12:51.482 --> 12:53.781
No. No, Sue.

12:53.948 --> 12:55.379
No!

12:55.458 --> 12:57.843
[ Voice echoes ]

12:59.379 --> 13:01.114
It's true, Axl.
I did apply to your school,

13:01.201 --> 13:03.549
but I'm sorry. I just love
East Indiana so much.

13:03.632 --> 13:05.489
- [ Groans ]
- I love the campus. I love the rotunda.

13:05.569 --> 13:07.087
They have a really good
psychology department.

13:07.167 --> 13:09.141
Ow! It's like acid in my ears!

13:09.246 --> 13:12.414
See? I knew we should have told
him right when I told you guys.

13:12.490 --> 13:13.923
Oh, my God.
You knew about this?

13:14.039 --> 13:16.854
You two supposed adults
let this happen?

13:17.006 --> 13:19.053
All right, listen,
when Sue told us,

13:19.132 --> 13:20.408
dad and I called
a family meeting.

13:20.527 --> 13:22.967
We decided there was
no sense in telling you the news

13:23.083 --> 13:24.429
unless she got accepted.

13:24.569 --> 13:26.480
You had a family meeting
without me?!

13:26.616 --> 13:27.367
[ Sighs ] All right.

13:27.443 --> 13:28.943
I know this is coming
out of the blue,

13:29.048 --> 13:30.427
but if you really think
about it,

13:30.504 --> 13:32.299
is this honestly
that big a deal?

13:32.379 --> 13:34.202
It's a huge deal!
College is supposed to be

13:34.303 --> 13:35.687
the best four years of my life,

13:35.769 --> 13:37.649
and now two of those years
are gonna be with Sue.

13:37.736 --> 13:39.456
I'll be at a party
being awesome,

13:39.555 --> 13:42.182
and in walks Sue with
her big tubey water head.

13:42.300 --> 13:43.616
This is
the worst possible thing

13:43.688 --> 13:44.962
that could ever happen
to a person!

13:45.087 --> 13:47.084
I think your Aunt Edie
might disagree with that.

13:47.175 --> 13:48.435
Okay, stop freaking out, Axl.

13:48.555 --> 13:49.962
I'm probably not even
gonna get in.

13:50.043 --> 13:51.678
They think I wanna shoot
at cars.

13:51.795 --> 13:53.045
Oh, no. They're gonna want
another Heck.

13:53.128 --> 13:54.196
I'm like royalty up there.

13:54.270 --> 13:55.803
Well, guess what?
She may be going there,

13:55.895 --> 13:57.502
but I'm not.
I'm getting off this train

13:57.609 --> 13:59.347
and starting my new life in...

14:00.259 --> 14:01.875
Bear's Neck, South Dakota!

14:01.981 --> 14:03.800
That's where I'll be
living out my life.

14:03.919 --> 14:06.411
I am outta here!
Thanks for 20 crappy years!

14:19.863 --> 14:21.610
Excuse me?
My name is Brick.

14:21.858 --> 14:24.669
Uh... Steen... Johnson.

14:25.319 --> 14:26.892
I'm in the market
for some chips today.

14:27.532 --> 14:28.554
Knock yourself out.

14:28.996 --> 14:29.962
[ Chuckles nervously ]

14:32.546 --> 14:34.002
Actually, I've decided not
to do this.

14:34.106 --> 14:37.398
I'm not a risk-taking person,
you know, chip-wise,

14:37.527 --> 14:39.038
and Mesquite--

14:39.113 --> 14:40.784
you never really know
how that's gonna go down.

14:42.718 --> 14:44.012
[ Crash ]

14:50.791 --> 14:51.879
Axl!

14:53.268 --> 14:55.225
Come on, Axl. You're not gonna
live in Bear's Neck.

14:55.330 --> 14:57.024
This place is an armpit!

14:57.178 --> 14:59.123
[ Chuckles ] I'm sure
it's lovely for you folks.

14:59.335 --> 15:01.652
Man: - All aboard!
- [ Bell clanging ]

15:01.961 --> 15:03.292
Axl!

15:19.643 --> 15:20.894
Axl!

15:22.825 --> 15:24.763
- [ Horn blows ]
- [ Shouts inaudibly ]

15:29.181 --> 15:30.293
Crap!

15:34.363 --> 15:35.659
Can I sit next to you?

15:35.758 --> 15:37.000
Yeah, sure. Why?

15:37.132 --> 15:39.563
No reason. I just wanna
stay close to you

15:39.650 --> 15:41.602
during this difficult time
with Aunt Edie.

15:41.875 --> 15:43.481
Also, if this friend of mine
shows up

15:43.566 --> 15:45.395
and wants to drag me away,
can you protect me?

15:45.480 --> 15:46.884
He's a little bigger than you.

15:47.009 --> 15:48.456
Oh, and he might be drunk.

15:48.561 --> 15:49.253
Not now, Brick.

15:49.320 --> 15:51.540
I'm researching jobs that don't
require a college degree

15:51.625 --> 15:53.827
since I won't be getting one.

15:55.055 --> 15:57.552
You know, Sue, your typo really
isn't that big of a deal.

15:57.684 --> 15:59.885
Did you know in the play
"Julius Caesar,"

15:59.980 --> 16:01.907
Shakespeare wrote a line
about a clock striking three,

16:02.009 --> 16:04.669
even though clocks didn't even
exist in Ancient Rome?

16:04.739 --> 16:07.814
- Really? - Yeah, and he's
the greatest writer of all time.

16:07.923 --> 16:09.640
You know, as long as the spirit

16:09.722 --> 16:11.086
of what you wanna say
comes through,

16:11.173 --> 16:13.245
I don't think colleges will care
about one little mistake.

16:13.321 --> 16:14.310
[ Door opens ]

16:14.637 --> 16:16.497
Trust me, Sue. If I've learned
anything from Aunt Edie,

16:16.615 --> 16:18.837
- it's that you can't live your life in fear.
- [ Door closes ]

16:19.336 --> 16:20.114
[ Gasps ]

16:24.138 --> 16:26.910
<i>Man over PA:</i>
<i>Next stop-- Yankton.</i>

16:27.054 --> 16:29.148
<i>Yankton is the next stop.</i>

16:29.243 --> 16:30.183
[ Sighs ]

16:30.261 --> 16:31.504
I suppose you're here
to tell me all the reasons

16:31.586 --> 16:34.737
it's not gonna be so bad
having Sue go to my college.

16:34.833 --> 16:37.839
Nope. Actually, that's got
nothing to do with you.

16:38.266 --> 16:40.893
Uh, my dorky sister
at <i> my</i> college?

16:40.988 --> 16:42.502
I think it has everything
to do with me.

16:43.388 --> 16:44.962
Sue doesn't have to live
her life

16:45.033 --> 16:46.756
based on what you want.

16:46.915 --> 16:47.669
So what are you saying?

16:47.743 --> 16:49.927
I'm just supposed to roll over
and be happy about this?

16:50.069 --> 16:52.347
I'm saying if Sue gets
into East Indiana

16:52.435 --> 16:54.325
and she wants to go there,
she's going there.

16:54.459 --> 16:57.252
How you feel about it
is up to you.

16:57.541 --> 16:59.841
If it makes you feel any better...
[ Sighs ]

17:00.066 --> 17:02.721
by the time she gets there,
you'll be old enough to drink.

17:07.056 --> 17:10.690
Okay, so the funeral home
came and got Aunt Edie,

17:10.796 --> 17:13.064
so we should get to
the hotel and settle in.

17:13.143 --> 17:14.638
It's gonna be a rough day
tomorrow.

17:14.797 --> 17:16.364
Hold it. Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.
Hold on.

17:16.454 --> 17:17.819
We gotta wait for your mom
to get off the train.

17:17.887 --> 17:19.323
- Can't she walk? - We gotta get outta here.
- I'm freezing.

17:19.406 --> 17:20.492
Trust me, this wouldn't be
a good day

17:20.580 --> 17:22.347
for me <i> not</i> to wait for your mom.

17:22.625 --> 17:24.290
[ Sighs ]

17:25.772 --> 17:27.406
[ Brakes squeal ]

17:28.160 --> 17:29.824
There they are.
That's them.

17:31.792 --> 17:32.983
[ Dog panting ]

17:33.074 --> 17:34.404
- What the hell?
- Thanks so much!

17:34.503 --> 17:40.470
Oh! Oh! I'm here. I'm okay.
I'm okay.

17:40.565 --> 17:42.485
So sorry if I worried you guys,

17:42.585 --> 17:44.160
but when the train
left without me,

17:44.248 --> 17:45.155
I couldn't get a signal,

17:45.245 --> 17:46.673
and there was nobody
at the train station,

17:46.769 --> 17:48.931
and the office with the phone
in it was locked.

17:49.050 --> 17:50.821
So I just started walking.

17:50.933 --> 17:52.703
I mean, I cried
a little bit first,

17:52.797 --> 17:54.021
but all I could think was,

17:54.116 --> 17:55.678
I am gonna freeze to death
out here,

17:55.774 --> 17:57.531
and my husband and my kids
are trying to call me,

17:57.616 --> 17:59.084
and they can't reach me,
and they're just gonna

17:59.151 --> 18:01.686
hold out hope
until some soybean farmer

18:01.772 --> 18:04.752
finds my partially thawed corpse
in the spring.

18:04.849 --> 18:05.880
[ Chuckles ]

18:06.985 --> 18:08.798
[ Train horn
blowing in distance ]

18:11.145 --> 18:16.113
Oh... my... God.

18:16.198 --> 18:18.748
You didn't even notice
I was gone, did you?!

18:18.821 --> 18:19.356
<i>- What?</i>
- We were so worried.

18:19.444 --> 18:20.909
- I didn't...
- Of course we did.

18:22.724 --> 18:23.464
Aw!

18:24.583 --> 18:26.876
Get your patty hands off me!

18:27.519 --> 18:28.466
[ Door squeaks ]

18:29.138 --> 18:31.131
Whew.
[ Exhales deeply ]

18:32.353 --> 18:33.444
[ Exhales deeply ]

18:35.207 --> 18:37.053
<i>This</i> is the Leilani?

18:37.526 --> 18:38.864
[ Vacuum whirring ]

18:38.938 --> 18:41.708
I thought Aunt Edie said
it was a slice of paradise.

18:41.946 --> 18:43.286
It's a slice of something.

18:43.383 --> 18:44.241
Maybe it's a good thing

18:44.347 --> 18:46.228
Aunt Edie never saw it
like this.

18:46.572 --> 18:49.325
<i>Frankie: But the funny thing</i>
<i>was the darker it got,</i>

18:50.301 --> 18:53.954
<i>the more magical the Leilani</i>
<i>became.</i>

18:55.748 --> 18:59.247
<i>[ Slow-tempo Polynesian music playing ]</i>

19:01.085 --> 19:03.053
[ Sighs ] Here.

19:03.449 --> 19:05.637
It's the fruitest, girliest
drink I could find.

19:05.748 --> 19:07.219
Oh, thanks.

19:07.309 --> 19:10.995
You owe me $2.50,
and by the way,

19:11.075 --> 19:14.070
if you do decide you want
to go to my school...

19:14.158 --> 19:16.630
[ Inhales deeply ]
I'd be okay with it.

19:16.722 --> 19:20.975
[ Gasps ] <i> Really?</i>
Oh, that is so nice, Axl.

19:21.053 --> 19:22.810
Yeah, not doing it for you.

19:22.924 --> 19:24.933
It's my final karmic payment.

19:25.014 --> 19:27.541
The way I see it, I <i> gotta</i>
be even with Aunt Edie now

19:27.612 --> 19:29.180
'cause... you going to my school

19:29.279 --> 19:31.567
is the worst possible thing
that could ever happen to me.

19:31.664 --> 19:33.253
Come on.
I bet if I end up there,

19:33.337 --> 19:35.322
we'll definitely have
some good times.

19:35.403 --> 19:36.850
- Nope, not even one.
- Not one?

19:36.937 --> 19:37.896
- No.
- Not even one?

19:37.984 --> 19:40.335
- Not even one--
- What's with the book?

19:40.478 --> 19:43.342
- Thought you were living life.
- Yeah, it's not for me.

19:43.502 --> 19:45.768
I decided there's two types
of people in the world--

19:45.913 --> 19:48.011
people who are meant to live
their life to the fullest

19:48.098 --> 19:50.597
and people who are meant
to read about those people.

19:50.749 --> 19:52.520
I'm the latter.

19:54.023 --> 19:56.462
So... you just drive
straight up Route 30,

19:56.561 --> 19:58.779
and you'll see our sign that
says "Bushman Funeral Home."

19:58.860 --> 20:00.240
It's right across
from the turkey farm.

20:00.322 --> 20:02.173
Trust me,
you'll... smell it.

20:02.262 --> 20:04.691
[ Sighs ] Now should I get there
a couple hours early

20:04.780 --> 20:06.012
to fill out the paperwork?

20:06.080 --> 20:08.368
Uh, actually, your husband
already took care of that.

20:08.454 --> 20:10.547
- I spoke to him a few days ago.
- [ Papers rustling ]

20:11.129 --> 20:14.048
Oh. Great. Uh, but there's
still a bunch

20:14.132 --> 20:16.455
of permits and forms
I need to fill out

20:16.540 --> 20:18.650
'cause we brought the body
across state lines.

20:18.739 --> 20:20.546
Nope. All taken care of.

20:20.635 --> 20:22.142
Your husband filled out
everything and faxed it to me

20:22.237 --> 20:23.832
from his office in Indiana.

20:24.260 --> 20:26.989
Oh. Okay.

20:27.284 --> 20:29.639
Well, I guess I'll just
write you a check, then.

20:29.726 --> 20:30.995
You're all paid in full.

20:31.077 --> 20:33.509
Your husband split it
between five credit cards.

20:34.013 --> 20:35.485
You don't have to worry
about anything.

20:35.573 --> 20:36.688
All you have to do is show up.

20:36.837 --> 20:38.176
[ Briefcase latches click ]

20:40.748 --> 20:43.117
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

20:43.522 --> 20:46.691
<i>♪</i>

20:48.419 --> 20:49.968
[ Exhales ]
What's that for?

20:50.144 --> 20:51.747
Everything.

20:52.949 --> 20:56.395
Frankie: <i>You know, Mike may not be a nurturer
in the typical sense,</i>

20:57.277 --> 21:00.422
<i>but he picks me up in ways
I don't even know about.</i>

21:01.529 --> 21:03.851
<i>And that night he picked me up
three more times</i>

21:03.945 --> 21:06.959
<i>on the way to the room.
I picked him up once.</i>

21:07.214 --> 21:10.214
<i>Yeah. We partied hard
Aunt Edie-style.</i>

21:11.140 --> 21:14.945
<i>Hey, she lived 'till 96,
can't be that bad for you.</i>

